r. Sneer\n|\n|\n|-\n|1986\n|''Across from the Garden of Allah''\n|Douglas\n|\n|Comedy Theatre\n|-\n|1988\n|''[[The Miser]]''\n|Harpagon\n|\n|\n|-\n|1988\n|''[[Hapgood (play)|Hapgood]]''\n|Blair\n|\n|Aldwych Theatre\n|-\n|1989\n|''The Spirit of Man''\n|Reverend Jonathan Guerdon\n|\n|\n|-\n|1989\n|''[[Shadowlands (play)|Shadowlands]]''\n|C.S. Lewis\n|\n|Queens Theatre\n|-\n|1990\n|''[[Shadowlands (play)|Shadowlands]]''\n|C.S. Lewis\n|\n|Brooks Atkins Theatre\n|-\n|1991\n|''[[The Trials of Oz]]''\n|Brian Leary\n|\n|\n|-\n|1992\n|''[[Flea bites|Flea Bites]]''\n|Kryst\n|\n|\n|-\n|1999\n|''[[King Lear]]''\n|Lear\n|[[Royal Shakespeare Company|RSC]]\n|[[Barbican Centre|Barbican]]\n|}\n\n== Awards and nominations ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Title\n!Accolade\n!Category\n!Result\n|-\n|1977\n|''[[Privates on Parade]]''\n|[[Laurence Olivier Award]]\n|[[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Actor in a Supporting Role|Best Actor in a Supporting Role]]\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|1981\n|''[[Yes Minister]]''\n|[[Broadcasting Press Guild|Broadcasting Press Guild Award]]\n|[[Broadcasting Press Guild|Best Actor in a Light Entertainment Program]]\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|1982\n|''Yes Minister''\n|[[British Academy Television Awards|British Academy Television Award]]\n|[[British Academy Television Award for Best Entertainment Performance|Best Light Entertainment Performance]]\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|1983\n|''Yes Minister''\n|[[British Academy Television Awards|British Academy Television Award]]\n|[[British Academy Television Award for Best Entertainment Performance|Best Light Entertainment Performance]]\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|1987\n|''[[Yes, Prime Minister]]''\n|[[British Academy Television Awards|British Academy Television Award]]\n|[[British Academy Television Award for Best Entertainment Performance|Best Light Entertainment Performance]]\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|1988\n|''Yes, Prime Minister''\n|[[British Academy Television Awards|British Academy Television Award]]\n|[[British Academy Television Award for Best Entertainment Per