{"title_page": "The Echoing Green", "text_new": "[[File:Songs of Innocence and of Experience, copy Y, 1825 (Metropolitan Museum of Art) object 6.jpg|thumb|250px|''Songs of Innocence and of Experience'', copy Y, 1825 (Metropolitan Museum of Art) object 6 (The Echoing Green 1)]]\n{{about|the poem|the synthpop band|The Echoing Green (band)}}\n\n\"'''The Echoing Green'''\" (or Ecchoing Green) is a poem by [[William Blake]] published in ''[[Songs of Innocence]]'' in 1789. The poem talks about merry sounds and images which accompany the children playing outdoors. Then, an old man happily remembers when he enjoyed playing with his friends during his own childhood. The last stanza depicts the little ones being weary when the sun has descended and going to their mother to rest after playing many games.\n\nU mom\n\n==Gallery==\nScholarly editions all place \"The Echoing Green\"  as the sixth object in the print order for the ''Songs of Innocence and of Experience''. The following, represents a comparison of several of the extant copies of the poem, their print date, their order in that particular printing of the poems, and their holding institution:<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.blakearchive.org/exist/blake/archive/comparison.xq?selection=compare&copies=all&bentleynum=B6&copyid=songsie.b&java=  | title =  Comparison of Songs of Innocence's  \"The Echoing Green\"| editors =Morris Eaves, Robert N. Essick, and Joseph Viscomi | publisher = [[William Blake Archive]]| accessdate = February 7, 2014}}</ref>\n<gallery>\nSongs of Innocence and of Experience, copy C, 1789, 1794 (Library of Congress) object 13 (The Echoing Green).jpg| Copy C, 1789, 1794 ([[Library of Congress]]) object 13 (The Echoing Green 1)\nSongs of Innocence and of Experience, copy C, 1789, 1794 (Library of Congress) object 14 (The Echoing Green).jpg| Copy C, 1789, 1794 ([[Library of Congress]]) object 14 (The Echoing Green 2)\nSongs of Innocence and of Experience, copy Y, 1825 (Metropolitan Museum of Art) object 6.jpg| Copy Y, 1825 ([[Metropolitan Museum of Art]]) object 6 (The Echoing Green 1)\nSongs of Innocence and of Experience, copy Y, 1825 (Metropolitan Museum of Art) object 7 (The Echoing Green).jpg|Copy Y, 1825 ([[Metropolitan Museum of Art]]) object 7 (The Echoing Green 2)\nBlake echoing green 1.jpg|Copy Z, 1826 ([[Library of Congress]]) object 6 (The Echoing Green 1)\nBlake echoing green.jpg|Copy Z, 1826 ([[Library of Congress]]) object 7 (The Echoing Green 2)\nSongs of Innocence and of Experience, copy AA, 1826 (The Fitzwilliam Museum) object 6 (The Echoing Green).jpg|Copy AA, 1826 ([[The Fitzwilliam Museum]]) object 6 (The Echoing Green 1)\nSongs of Innocence and of Experience, copy AA, 1826 (The Fitzwilliam Museum) object 7 (The Echoing Green).jpg|Copy AA, 1826 ([[The Fitzwilliam Museum]]) object 7 (The Echoing Green 2)\n</gallery>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n===Works cited===\n* ''Oxford Student Study Guide'', 'William Blake'.\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.blakearchive.org/exist/blake/archive/comparison.xq?selection=compare&copies=all&bentleynum=B6&copyid=songsie.e&java= A Comparison of Extant copies of the original prints of  The Echoing Green] available from the [[William Blake Archive]]\n{{Wikisource|The Echoing Green}}\n\n{{William Blake|lit}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Echoing Green}}\n[[Category:1789 poems]]\n[[Category:Songs of Innocence and of Experience]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Songs of Innocence and of Experience, copy Y, 1825 (Metropolitan Museum of Art) object 6.jpg|thumb|250px|''Songs of Innocence and of Experience'', copy Y, 1825 (Metropolitan Museum of Art) object 6 (The Echoing Green 1)]]\n{{about|the poem|the synthpop band|The Echoing Green (band)}}\n\n\"'''The Echoing Green'''\" (or Ecchoing Green) is a poem by [[William Blake]] published in ''[[Songs of Innocence]]'' in 1789. The poem talks about merry sounds and images which accompany the children playing outdoors. Then, an old man happily remembers when he enjoyed playing with his friends during his own childhood. The last stanza depicts the little ones being weary when the sun has descended and going to their mother to rest after playing many games.\n\n==Style==\nThe poem follows the structure of a day\u2014 'the sun does arise' in the beginning of the first verse, and 'the sun does descend' in the middle of the third stanza, and can be read as a metaphor for human life.  The poem is the contrast of innocence and experience, but also the contrast between perception of joys and sorrows. What is happening on the Green will happen again, shown by the 'old folk' who watch the children and reminisce about their own childhood on the Green. The whole poem is written in six sentences with much repetition.\n\n== The poem ==\n{{quote|<poem>\nThe Sun does arise,\nAnd make happy the skies.\nThe merry bells ring\nTo welcome the Spring.\nThe sky-lark and thrush,\nThe birds of the bush,\nSing louder around,\nTo the bells cheerful sound.\nWhile our sports shall be seen\nOn the Echoing Green.\n\nOld John with white hair\nDoes laugh away care,\nSitting under the oak,\nAmong the old folk,\nThey laugh at our play,\nAnd soon they all say.\nSuch such were the joys.\nWhen we all girls & boys,\nIn our youth-time were seen,\nOn the Echoing Green.\n\nTill the little ones weary\nNo more can be merry\nThe sun does descend,\nAnd our sports have an end:\nRound the laps of their mothers,\nMany sisters and brothers,\nLike birds in their nest,\nAre ready for rest;\nAnd sport no more seen,\nOn the darkening Green.<ref>{{cite book |last=Blake |first=William |author-link=William Blake |editor-last=Erdman |editor-first=David V. |editor-link=David V. Erdman |title=The Complete Poetry and Prose |date=1988 |publisher=Anchor Books |isbn=0385152132 |edition=Newly revised |page=8 |url=https://archive.org/details/completepoetrypr00blak/page/}}</ref></poem>}}\n\n==Gallery==\nScholarly editions all place \"The Echoing Green\"  as the sixth object in the print order for the ''Songs of Innocence and of Experience''. The following, represents a comparison of several of the extant copies of the poem, their print date, their order in that particular printing of the poems, and their holding institution:<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.blakearchive.org/exist/blake/archive/comparison.xq?selection=compare&copies=all&bentleynum=B6&copyid=songsie.b&java=  | title =  Comparison of Songs of Innocence's  \"The Echoing Green\"| editors =Morris Eaves, Robert N. Essick, and Joseph Viscomi | publisher = [[William Blake Archive]]| accessdate = February 7, 2014}}</ref>\n<gallery>\nSongs of Innocence and of Experience, copy C, 1789, 1794 (Library of Congress) object 13 (The Echoing Green).jpg| Copy C, 1789, 1794 ([[Library of Congress]]) object 13 (The Echoing Green 1)\nSongs of Innocence and of Experience, copy C, 1789, 1794 (Library of Congress) object 14 (The Echoing Green).jpg| Copy C, 1789, 1794 ([[Library of Congress]]) object 14 (The Echoing Green 2)\nSongs of Innocence and of Experience, copy Y, 1825 (Metropolitan Museum of Art) object 6.jpg| Copy Y, 1825 ([[Metropolitan Museum of Art]]) object 6 (The Echoing Green 1)\nSongs of Innocence and of Experience, copy Y, 1825 (Metropolitan Museum of Art) object 7 (The Echoing Green).jpg|Copy Y, 1825 ([[Metropolitan Museum of Art]]) object 7 (The Echoing Green 2)\nBlake echoing green 1.jpg|Copy Z, 1826 ([[Library of Congress]]) object 6 (The Echoing Green 1)\nBlake echoing green.jpg|Copy Z, 1826 ([[Library of Congress]]) object 7 (The Echoing Green 2)\nSongs of Innocence and of Experience, copy AA, 1826 (The Fitzwilliam Museum) object 6 (The Echoing Green).jpg|Copy AA, 1826 ([[The Fitzwilliam Museum]]) object 6 (The Echoing Green 1)\nSongs of Innocence and of Experience, copy AA, 1826 (The Fitzwilliam Museum) object 7 (The Echoing Green).jpg|Copy AA, 1826 ([[The Fitzwilliam Museum]]) object 7 (The Echoing Green 2)\n</gallery>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n===Works cited===\n* ''Oxford Student Study Guide'', 'William Blake'.\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.blakearchive.org/exist/blake/archive/comparison.xq?selection=compare&copies=all&bentleynum=B6&copyid=songsie.e&java= A Comparison of Extant copies of the original prints of  The Echoing Green] available from the [[William Blake Archive]]\n{{Wikisource|The Echoing Green}}\n\n{{William Blake|lit}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Echoing Green}}\n[[Category:1789 poems]]\n[[Category:Songs of Innocence and of Experience]]\n", "name_user": "172.251.144.213", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Typo)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Echoing_Green"}
{"title_page": "Andy Todd (footballer, born 1974)", "text_new": "{{for|the Rotherham and Mansfield player|Andy Todd (footballer, born 1979)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name          = Andy Todd\n| image          = AndyTodd01.jpg\n| fullname       = Andrew John James Todd\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1974|9|21|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Derby]], England\n| height         = \n| position       = [[Defender (association football)|Centre Back]]\n| currentclub    = \n| youthyears1    =           |youthclubs1 = [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]]\n| years1         = 1992\u20131995 |clubs1 = [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]]                |caps1 = 8   |goals1 = 0\n| years2         = 1995      |clubs2 = \u2192 [[Swindon Town]] (loan)                           |caps2 = 13  |goals2 = 0\n| years3         = 1995\u20131999 |clubs3 = [[Bolton Wanderers]]                                |caps3 = 84  |goals3 = 2\n| years4         = 1999\u20132002 |clubs4 = [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]]        |caps4 = 40  |goals4 = 1\n| years5         = 2002      |clubs5 = \u2192 [[Grimsby Town]] (loan)                           |caps5 = 12  |goals5 = 3\n| years6         = 2002\u20132007 |clubs6 = [[Blackburn Rovers]]                                |caps6 = 88  |goals6 = 4\n| years7         = 2003      |clubs7 = \u2192 [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] (loan)                   |caps7 = 7   |goals7 = 0\n| years8         = 2007\u20132009 |clubs8 = [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]]                  |caps8 = 30  |goals8 = 1\n| years9         = 2008\u20132009 |clubs9 = \u2192 [[Northampton Town F.C.|Northampton Town]] (loan) |caps9 = 7   |goals9 = 0\n| years10        = 2009\u20132011 |clubs10 = [[Perth Glory]]                                    |caps10 = 41 |goals10 = 0\n| years11        = 2011      |clubs11 = [[Oldham Athletic A.F.C.|Oldham Athletic]]         |caps11 = 6  |goals11 = 0\n| years12        = 2011      |clubs12 = [[Hereford United F.C.|Hereford United]]           |caps12 = 4  |goals12 = 0\n| years13        = 2013      |clubs13 = [[Armadale SC|Armadale]]                           |caps13 = 2  |goals13 = 0\n| totalcaps = 342 | totalgoals = 11\n| manageryears1  = 2014\u20132016\n| managerclubs1 = [[Linfield F.C.|Linfield]] (assistant)\n| manageryears2  = 2016\n| managerclubs2 = [[Newport County A.F.C.|Newport County]] (assistant)\n| manageryears3 = 2016\u20132018\n| managerclubs3 = [[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]] (first-team coach)\n| manageryears4 = 2019\n| managerclubs4 = [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] (assistant manager)\n}}\n\n'''Andrew John James Todd''' (born 21 September 1974) is an English [[Association football|football]] coach and former player. His father is former [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]] and [[England national football team|England]] defender [[Colin Todd]] who was manager of [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]] when Andy made his debut.\n\n==Playing career==\n\n===Middlesbrough===\nBorn in [[Derby]], Derbyshire, Todd attended Hermitage Comprehensive School (Chester le Street). He was initially a trainee at [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]] and made his debut in 1992. He was loaned to [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]] shortly before leaving Boro in August 1995 to join [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]] for a transfer fee of \u00a3250,000.\n\n===Bolton Wanderers===\nHe scored two goals in total for Bolton over a four-year period, winning the 1996\u201397 Division One championship in the process. Todd left Bolton under a cloud, after allegedly breaking assistant manager [[Phil Brown (footballer, born 1959)|Phil Brown]]'s jaw and cheekbone in an incident at a team bonding session.\n\n===Charlton Athletic===\nTodd then moved to [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]], another Division One club, and won Division One for a second time. In Charlton's first season back in the Premiership, Todd scored his first and what turned out to be only Charlton goal against Leicester City in April 2001.<ref>{{cite news \n|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/1253014.stm\n|title=Bartlett stunner seals Charlton win\n|publisher=BBC   \n|date=1 April 2001 |accessdate=26 November 2009}}</ref> However, a training fracas with a then unnamed player (who was later revealed to be [[Dean Kiely]]), meant that he was on a knife-edge at the club. Initially welcomed back, he was loaned to [[Grimsby Town F.C.|Grimsby Town]] in February 2002, who at the time were struggling in Division One. Todd scored three goals in twelve league games for the Mariners, helping the club keep their place in the division.\n\n===Blackburn Rovers===\nIn May 2002, Todd left for Blackburn, but found first team opportunities hard to come by. Soon after breaking into the team in January 2003, he was sent off against [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham]] for kicking [[Christophe Dugarry]] in an [[off the ball]] incident. His first Rovers goal was in a 3\u20132 victory over [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]] towards the end of that season.\n\nTodd was put on the transfer list in 2003/04 and was loaned to [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]]. Good performances prompted a recall and Todd was thrust straight back into Rovers' first eleven with the team struggling near the bottom of the league. Todd won Rovers' player of the year award.\n\nIn 2004/05, Todd was handed the Rovers' captaincy by [[Mark Hughes]] following the departure of [[Barry Ferguson]] to [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]], a recognition of his continued solid performances. He once again won the player of the year and then led Rovers to European qualification the following season.\n\nTodd elbowed [[Robin van Persie]] in the head, drawing blood, near the end of a 2005 [[FA Cup Semi Final]] against [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]]. The [[the Football Association|FA]] subsequently cleared him of any wrongdoing.\n\nTodd's name came up in the [[2006 allegations of corruption in English football]]. Then-[[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]] manager [[Harry Redknapp]] was secretly filmed discussing the possibility of buying Todd with agent Peter Harrison, which is illegal under FA rules. However, the programme merely showed Harrison approaching Redknapp and asking direct questions which Redknapp answered. Redknapp simply stated, \"Yeah, I'd have him, I like Toddy, he's a tough bastard.\"\n\nHe has however found first team opportunities hard to come by during the latter stages of the 2006\u20132007 season, after talks with Todd, Mark Hughes let it be known that he was available for transfer, [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]], [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]], [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]], [[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]] and [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]] all expressed an interest.\n\n===Derby County===\nTodd joined [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]], a newly-promoted Premier League club, for an undisclosed fee believed to be around \u00a3750,000 on 7 July 2007.<ref name=\"toddjoinsderby\">{{cite web | title=Todd joins Derby| work=lancashiretelegraph.co.uk | url=http://www.lancashiretelegraph.co.uk/news/1527918.todd_joins_derby/| accessdate=7 Jul 2007}}</ref> He scored a late equaliser on his debut against Portsmouth on 11 August 2007.<ref name=\"derby2-2pompey\">{{cite news | title=Derby 2\u20132 Portsmouth|publisher=BBC  | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/6931060.stm| accessdate=11 Aug 2007 | date=11 August 2007}}</ref> However, his performance level soon dropped and after making two mistakes in Derby's 1\u20134 FA Cup defeat to Preston,<ref name=\"derby1-4preston\">{{cite news | title=Derby 1\u20134 Preston|publisher=BBC  | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/fa_cup/7197711.stm| accessdate=26 Jan 2008 | date=26 January 2008| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080128212120/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/fa_cup/7197711.stm| archivedate= 28 January 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref> Derby boss [[Paul Jewell]] dropped him. It was announced on 8 May 2008 that Todd was not in Jewell's plans for his restructuring of the Derby squad following relegation and he would be allowed to leave on a free transfer.<ref name=\"ramsreadytotrimsquad\">{{cite web| title=Rams ready to trim squad| work=thisisderbyshire.co.uk| url=http://www.thisisderbyshire.co.uk/news/Rams-ready-trim-squad/article-211832-detail/article.html| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090508070627/http://www.thisisderbyshire.co.uk/news/Rams-ready-trim-squad/article-211832-detail/article.html| url-status=dead| archivedate=8 May 2009| accessdate=9 Jul 2008}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 November 2008, Todd joined [[Northampton Town F.C.|Northampton Town]] of [[Football League One|League One]] on loan until 3 January 2009. This was the first time Todd had played outside the top two tiers of English football.<ref name=\"northamptonagrredtoddloandeal\">{{cite news | title=Northampton agree Todd loan deal|publisher=BBC  | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/n/northampton_town/7746405.stm| accessdate=24 Nov 2008 | date=24 November 2008| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20081204072502/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/n/northampton_town/7746405.stm| archivedate= 4 December 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref> On 25 November 2008, Todd made his debut for ''The Cobblers'' in 2\u20131 victory against [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]].<ref name=\"northampton2-1leeds\">{{cite news | title=Northampton 2\u20131 Leeds|publisher=BBC  | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_2/7741662.stm| accessdate=25 Nov 2008 | date=25 November 2008| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20081203233624/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_2/7741662.stm| archivedate= 3 December 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref> He returned to Derby County in January 2009, after featuring in 7 league games for Northampton.<ref name=\"hinescould\">{{cite web| title=Loab recruit Hines could be in line to face United| work=Derby Telegraph| url=http://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/Hines-line-face-United/story-11642896-detail/story.html| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140307144233/http://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/Hines-line-face-United/story-11642896-detail/story.html| url-status=dead| archivedate=7 March 2014| accessdate=7 March 2014}}</ref> His first game for Derby after returning from Northampton was the League Cup semi-final first leg against [[Manchester United]], with Todd helping Derby to a 1\u20130 victory. Todd also played in the 2nd leg of the semi-final, but could not prevent Derby losing 4\u20133 on aggregate. Todd appeared regularly at the end of the season, and his solid performances led to rumours that manager [[Nigel Clough]] would offer Todd a new 1-year contract. However, it was later announced that Todd would not be offered an extension when his contract expired at the end of the 2008/09 season,<ref name=\"Toddexit\">{{cite web| title= Defender Todd set for Rams exit door| work= therams.co.uk| url= http://therams.co.uk/stories/defender-todd-set-for-rams-exit-door| accessdate= 1 May 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090504081855/http://therams.co.uk/stories/defender-todd-set-for-rams-exit-door| archivedate= 4 May 2009| url-status= dead| df= dmy-all}}</ref> which saw Todd linked with a possible move to Australia with [[Sydney FC]] and [[Perth Glory]].\n\n===Perth Glory===\nOn 22 April 2009, the [[Sydney Morning Herald]] reported that Todd signed for [[A-League]] club [[Perth Glory]] and would see out the rest of his career playing in Australia.<ref name=\"andytoddsigns\">{{cite news |title=Meissner is cashed up for kick-off |work=The Sydney Morning Herald | url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/sport/football/a-league/meissner-is-cashed-up-for-kickoff/2009/04/21/1240079671060.html?page=2 |accessdate=22 April 2009 | date=22 April 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090508075853/http://www.smh.com.au/news/sport/football/a-league/meissner-is-cashed-up-for-kickoff/2009/04/21/1240079671060.html?page=2| archivedate= 8 May 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref> Todd completed the move to Australia on 18 May 2009.<ref>{{Cite web| title= Todd completes Aussie switch| publisher= Derby Evening Telegraph| url= http://therams.co.uk/stories/todd-completes-aussie-switch| accessdate= 18 May 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090521120820/http://therams.co.uk/stories/todd-completes-aussie-switch| archivedate= 21 May 2009| url-status= dead| df= dmy-all}}</ref> In what turned out to be an outstanding debut season performance, Todd was awarded [[Perth Glory]]'s 'Most Glorious Player' award for 2009\u201310.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Andy Todd wins MGP |publisher=a-league.com.au| url=http://www.a-league.com.au/default.aspx?s=newsdisplay&id=33244 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110616204718/http://www.a-league.com.au/default.aspx?s=newsdisplay&id=33244 |archivedate=16 June 2011 |accessdate=26 March 2010}}</ref> In January 2011 was released by the club, two months before the end of his contract, to allow him to find a new club during the transfer window.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Andy Todd released |publisher=footballaustralia.com.au| url=http://www.footballaustralia.com.au/perthglory/news-display/Andy-Todd-released/38287 |date=20 January 2011 |accessdate=7 March 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Oldham Athletic===\nOn 27 January 2011 he joined [[Oldham Athletic A.F.C.|Oldham Athletic]] after returning to the United Kingdom. He signed a contract for the remainder of the season.<ref name=\"Oldham Athletic sign Andy Todd and Aidan White\">{{cite web | title=Oldham Athletic sign Andy Todd and Aidan White|work=BBC Sport  | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/o/oldham_athletic/9377992.stm?| date=27 January 2011| accessdate=27 January 2011 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110201091326/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/o/oldham_athletic/9377992.stm| archivedate= 1 February 2011 | url-status= live}}</ref> Todd made his debut for the club coming on against [[Carlisle United]] at Brunton Park.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oldhamathletic.co.uk/page/NewsUpdate/0,,10337~2279711,00.html |accessdate=15 February 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120908094656/http://www.oldhamathletic.co.uk/page/NewsUpdate/0%2C%2C10337~2279711%2C00.html |archivedate=8 September 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.player.oldhamathletic.co.uk/latest-news/article/2279711|title=Second-half report|publisher=Oldham Athletic F.C.|date=15 February 2011|accessdate=7 March 2014}}{{subscription needed}}</ref><ref name=\"Games played by Andy Todd in 2010/2011\">{{Soccerbase season|7979|2010|name=Andy Todd|accessdate=7 March 2014}}</ref> Todd made his first start for the club when replacing the suspended [[Reuben Hazell]], starting against [[Carlisle United F.C|Carlisle United]] at Boundary Park.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oldhamathletic.co.uk/page/NewsUpdate/0,,10337~2293372,00.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110218220216/http://www.oldhamathletic.co.uk/page/NewsUpdate/0%2C%2C10337~2293372%2C00.html |archivedate=18 February 2011 |title=Todd starting call for Latics |publisher=Oldham Athletic F.C. |date=15 February 2011 |accessdate=7 March 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref> At the end of the season he was informed that he was out of contract and would not be offered a new deal.<ref name=\"Lactics offer new contracts\">{{cite news\n| title = Latics offer new contracts\n| url = http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,12874_6924077,00.html?\n| work=Sky Sports\n| date = 9 May 2011\n| accessdate = 10 May 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Hereford United===\nOn 14 October 2011 he moved to [[Hereford United F.C.|Hereford United]], on a non-contract basis having previously been on trial with [[Port Vale F.C.|Port Vale]] and [[Burton Albion F.C.|Burton Albion]].<ref>http://www.herefordunited.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10835~2481248,00.html {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20120805220742/http://www.herefordunited.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10835~2481248,00.html |date=5 August 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.player.herefordunited.co.uk/latest-news/article/2481248|title=Todd Agrees Non Contract Terms|publisher=Hereford United F.C.|date=14 October 2011|accessdate=7 March 2014}}{{subscription needed}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/15306716|title=Andy Todd sign non-contract Hereford United contract|publisher=BBC Sport|date=14 October 2011|accessdate=7 March 2014}}</ref> Todd was released by Hereford management after just four appearances in a Hereford shirt, due to a belief his legs had 'gone'. In response to some criticism of the decision from a number of Hereford fans, Hereford United Director of Football Gary Peters confirmed the decision to release the highly regarded fan's favourite on the club website (6 November 2011).<ref>{{cite web|title=Peters on Todd departure |work=Hereford United F.C. |url=http://www.herefordunited.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10835~2507189,00.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111108103435/http://www.herefordunited.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0%2C%2C10835~2507189%2C00.html |archivedate=8 November 2011 |accessdate=6 Nov 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===Armadale===\nIn March 2013 it was announced that he had signed for Australian club [[Armadale SC|Armadale]] in the [[Football West State League]], Premier Division.\n\n==Managerial career==\n\n===Linfield===\nOn 26 April 2014, it was announced that Todd was appointed as the assistant manager to [[Warren Feeney]] at [[NIFL Premiership]] club [[Linfield F.C.|Linfield]] in Northern Ireland, effective on 1 May 2014.<ref name=\"linfieldasst\">{{cite web|url=http://www.linfieldfc.com/latestnews.asp?nid=11899 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140502005225/http://www.linfieldfc.com/latestnews.asp?nid=11899 |url-status=dead |archivedate=2 May 2014 |title=Linfield FC announces appointment of new Manager |date=26 April 2014 |work=linfieldfc.com |accessdate=2 May 2014 }}</ref> Todd retained that position when [[David Healy (footballer)|David Healy]] was appointed the new manager of Linfield on 14 October 2015, as Feeney quit the job to become the assistant manager of [[Newport County A.F.C.|Newport County]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-3273043/Northern-Ireland-legend-David-Healy-takes-Warren-Feeney-Linfield-boss.html|title=Northern Ireland legend David Healy takes over from Warren Feeney as Linfield boss|publisher=Daily Mail|date=14 October 2015|accessdate=16 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Newport County===\nOn 15 January 2016, [[Warren Feeney]] was appointed as the manager of [[Football League Two|League Two]] club [[Newport County A.F.C.|Newport County]] with Todd appointed as assistant manager.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/35324509|title=Warren Feeney: Newport County appoint new manager|date=15 January 2016|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> A good start saw Newport gain 21 points from the first 12 games, but results then worsened. Newport finished the season in 22nd place in League Two, avoiding relegation. Feeney and Todd were sacked by Newport on 28 September 2016 with Newport County bottom of League Two having gained just 6 points from their first 9 matches of the 2016\u201317 season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/37494578|title=Newport County sack manager Warren Feeney|date=28 September 2016|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\n===Blackpool===\n\nFrom October 2016 to August 2018, he was the assistant under [[Gary Bowyer]] at [[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]].\n\n===Bradford City===\nIn March 2019, he was appointed as the assistant manager of [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]], again under Bowyer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bradfordcityfc.co.uk/news/2019/march/bowyer-takes-bantams-reins/|title=BOWYER TAKES BANTAMS REINS|website=www.bradfordcityfc.co.uk}}</ref> Todd left Bradford City in May 2019, following the club's relegation to League Two.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/sport/17629121.andy-todd-leaves-bradford-city/|title=Andy Todd leaves Bradford City|website=Bradford Telegraph and Argus}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n\n===England===\n<ref name=\"andytodd1\">{{cite web | title=Andy Todd profile| work=11v11.com | url=http://www.11v11.com/api/player/2539| accessdate=26 Sep 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"toodyearbook07-08\">{{cite book |last=Rollin |first=Glenda |author2=Rollin, Jack |title=SKY SPORTS FOOTBALL YEARBOOK 2007\u20132008 |edition=39th |publisher=Headline Publishing Group |isbn=978-0-7553-1664-9 |chapter=English League Players Directory |page=438 |year=2007 }}<!--|accessdate=26 November 2008 --></ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Andy Todd profile |work=dcfc.co.uk |url=http://www.dcfc.premiumtv.co.uk/page/ProfilesDetail/0,,10270~5566,00.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080516222848/http://www.dcfc.co.uk/page/ProfilesDetail/0%2C%2C10270~5566%2C00.html |archivedate=16 May 2008 |accessdate=26 Sep 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Andy Todd profile |work=oldhamathletic.co.uk |url=http://www.oldhamathletic.co.uk/page/ProfilesDetail/0,,10337~5566,00.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110305065440/http://www.oldhamathletic.co.uk/page/ProfilesDetail/0%2C%2C10337~5566%2C00.html |url-status=dead |archivedate=5 March 2011 |accessdate=6 May 2011 }}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Division\n!colspan=\"2\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|[[FA Cup]]\n!colspan=\"2\"|[[Football League Cup|League Cup]]\n!colspan=\"2\"|Europe\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other<ref>Includes other competitive competitions, including the [[Football League Trophy]] & the [[Football League play-offs|play-offs]]</ref>\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|[[1993\u201394 Football League|1993\u201394]]\n|r